03982nam a22005175i 9780822388869DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20082008ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223888697 a10.1515/97808223888692doi  a(DE-B1597)552575  a(OCoLC)1110261715  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aD973b.C51 2008 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a909/.098222221 aChambers, Iain, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMediterranean Crossings :bThe Politics of an Interrupted Modernity /cIain Chambers. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Many Voices -- t2. A Postcolonial Sea -- t3. Off the Map -- t4. Naples: A Porous Modernity -- t5. Between Shores -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe cultural theorist Iain Chambers is known for his historically grounded, philosophically informed, and politically pointed inquiries into issues of identity, alterity, and migration, and the challenge postcolonial studies poses to conventional Western thought. With Mediterranean Crossings, he challenges insufficient prevailing characterizations of the Mediterranean by offering a vibrant interdisciplinary and intercultural interpretation of the region's culture and history. The "Mediterranean" as a concept entered the European lexicon only in the early nineteenth century. As an object of study, it is the product of modern geographical, political, and historical classifications. Chambers contends that the region's fundamentally fluid, hybrid nature has long been obscured by the categories and strictures imposed by European discourse and government.In evocative and erudite prose, Chambers renders the Mediterranean a mutable space, profoundly marked by the linguistic, literary, culinary, musical, and intellectual dissemination of Arab, Jewish, Turkish, and Latin cultures. He brings to light histories of Mediterranean crossings-of people, goods, melodies, thought-that are rarely part of orthodox understandings. Chambers writes in a style that reflects the fluidity of the exchanges that have formed the region; he segues between major historical events and local daily routines, backwards and forwards in time, and from one part of the Mediterranean to another. A sea of endlessly overlapping cultural and historical currents, the Mediterranean exceeds the immediate constraints of nationalism and inflexible identity. It offers scholars an opportunity to rethink the past and present and to imagine a future beyond the confines of Western humanistic thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822388869zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822388869423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822388869.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles